"Fole, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Paston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Norfolk): habitational name, chiefly from Paston in Norfolk, probably derived from an Old English personal name <i>Pæcci</i> (genitive <i>Pæcces</i>) or Old English <i>pæsc(e)</i> (the source of northern English dialect <i>pash</i> ‘puddle’) + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","English (West Midlands): sometimes a variant of <b>Patstone</b>, a habitational name chiefly from the lost <i>Padston(e)</i> in Bromsgrove (Worcestershire), and occasionally from Padson in Inwardleigh (Devon). The Worcestershire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Padda</i> (genitive <i>Paddes</i>) + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The etymology of the Devon placename is uncertain due to a lack of medieval forms, though an early spelling suggests the final element is Old English <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs Thomas Paston was born about 1549, in Fole, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Thomas Aston about 1500, in Fole, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1549–":"umbes 1549–Surnud","1480–1551":"1480–1551","1544–Male":"1544–Surnud","1577–Male":"1577–Surnud","1518–1573":"1518–1573","1549–Female":"1549–Surnud","about 1549":"umbes 1549","1577":"1577","1544":